  <h2>How the {{ state.name }} Growing Season Actually Works</h2>

  {% set season = state.season or null %}
  {% set spring = season and season.frost and season.frost.spring or null %}
  {% set fall = season and season.frost and season.frost.fall or null %}
  {% set derived = season and season.derived or null %}
  {% set gdd = season and season.gdd and season.gdd.remaining or null %}

  {% set springStatus = spring and spring.status or null %}
  {% set fallStatus = fall and fall.status or null %}
  {% set frostFreeDays = derived and derived.frostFreeDays_p50 or null %}
  {% set fallSpread = derived and derived.fallSpreadDays50 or null %}
  {% set gddJul1 = gdd and gdd["07-01"] or null %}
  {% set gddAug1 = gdd and gdd["08-01"] or null %}

  {% if not season %}
    <p class="small">Season timing guidance isn’t available for this region yet.</p>

  {% elif springStatus == "frost_free" or fallStatus == "frost_free" %}
    <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
      This region is typically frost-free in the normals dataset, so the season is less about beating a hard frost cutoff and more about managing heat, moisture, and crop maturity.
    </p>

  {% else %}
    {% set seasonBand = "mid" %}
    {% if frostFreeDays %}
      {% if frostFreeDays <= 115 %}
        {% set seasonBand = "short" %}
      {% elif frostFreeDays >= 190 %}
        {% set seasonBand = "long" %}
      {% else %}
        {% set seasonBand = "mid" %}
      {% endif %}
    {% endif %}

    {% set runwayBand = "unknown" %}
    {% if gddJul1 is not null and gddAug1 is not null %}
      {% if gddJul1 >= 1700 and gddAug1 >= 900 %}
        {% set runwayBand = "high" %}
      {% elif gddJul1 <= 1000 or gddAug1 <= 300 %}
        {% set runwayBand = "low" %}
      {% else %}
        {% set runwayBand = "mid" %}
      {% endif %}
    {% endif %}

    {% if seasonBand == "short" and runwayBand == "high" %}
      <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
        {{ state.name }} tends to run as a short but productive season. The main challenge usually isn’t peak-summer heat — it’s getting warm-season crops established promptly enough to use it.
      </p>
    {% elif seasonBand == "short" %}
      <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
        {{ state.name }} rewards speed. The season window is short, and the back half often cools quickly, so variety maturity and staying on schedule matter more than almost anything else.
      </p>
    {% elif seasonBand == "long" and runwayBand == "high" %}
      <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
        {{ state.name }} usually gives gardeners more flexibility. A longer season and stronger late-summer heat make staggered planting and second rounds more realistic than in colder interior regions.
      </p>
    {% elif seasonBand == "long" %}
      <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
        {{ state.name }} usually has a forgiving season, but outcomes still depend on how well crops are matched to your local conditions and how quickly gardens warm in spring.
      </p>
    {% else %}
      <p class="small" style="margin-top:-0.25rem;">
        {{ state.name }} is mostly a timing-and-variety season. The biggest wins come from planting on time, matching maturity to the frost window, and using late-summer heat well.
      </p>
    {% endif %}

    <ul class="small" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
      {% if seasonBand == "short" %}
        <li><strong>Warm-season crops:</strong> do best when they’re established promptly after last frost.</li>
        <li><strong>Variety choice matters:</strong> short-season cultivars usually outperform longer-season bets.</li>
        <li><strong>Season extension helps:</strong> row cover and sheltered spots often make a noticeable difference.</li>
      {% elif seasonBand == "long" %}
        <li><strong>Stagger planting:</strong> it’s often more effective than putting everything in at once.</li>
        <li><strong>Fall gardening can be strong:</strong> many regions have enough runway for a real second wave.</li>
        <li><strong>Mid-summer management matters:</strong> water, fertility, and pest pressure often become the main limiters.</li>
      {% else %}
        <li><strong>Start on time:</strong> early establishment is the biggest controllable factor for warm-season success.</li>
        <li><strong>Match maturity to the window:</strong> reliable harvests usually come from realistic crop timing, not optimism.</li>
        <li><strong>Use late summer carefully:</strong> fast greens, roots, and compact crops usually make the best second round.</li>
      {% endif %}
    </ul>

    {% if fallSpread %}
      {% if fallSpread >= 35 %}
        <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
          Microclimate note: frost timing varies widely across {{ state.name }}, so sheltered gardens, urban sites, and warmer exposures can behave quite differently from colder open areas.
        </p>
      {% elif fallSpread <= 15 %}
        <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
          Microclimate note: frost timing is fairly consistent across much of {{ state.name }}, so regional averages are usually a solid starting point.
        </p>
      {% else %}
        <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.75rem;">
          Microclimate note: local conditions still matter here — low spots, exposed sites, and higher elevations often cool faster than the regional median suggests.
        </p>
      {% endif %}
    {% endif %}

    {% if gddAug1 is not null %}
      {% if gddAug1 >= 800 %}
        <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          Late-summer note: there’s often still meaningful heat left around early August, so second plantings of fast crops can be worthwhile.
        </p>
      {% elif gddAug1 <= 300 %}
        <p class="small muted" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          Late-summer note: by early August, the heat runway often tightens. Late plantings tend to do best when they’re fast, cold-tolerant, or protected.
        </p>
      {% endif %}
    {% endif %}

  {% endif %}
